type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, Danish, and Norwegian: topographic name for someone who lived in or by a small wood, from Middle English, Middle Low German, Danish, and Norwegian <i>holt</i>, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word. In England, the surname is widely distributed, but more common in Lancashire and Yorkshire than elsewhere."],"variants":[{"name":"Hohlt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Ordell.","North German: variant of   Holt   with the additional <i>h</i> reflecting the lengthened vowel or a variant of   Hohl   with the addition of excrescent <i>-t</i>.","Scandinavian: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holten","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Nils.","Dutch (also <b>Van Holten</b>) and North German: habitational name from any of the places so called, from Low German <i>holt</i> ‘holt, copse, small wood’. There are two in the Dutch province of Overijssel and another near Oberhausen in the Rhineland.","Danish: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holtan","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads so named, from the definite plural form of <i>holt</i> ‘small wood’ (see   Holt  )."]},{"name":"Holter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Selmer, Hilmar, Knute, Lars.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads in southeastern Norway, from the indefinite plural of <i>holt</i> ‘holt, small wood’ (see   Holt  ).","North German (also <b>Hölter</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places in Westphalia called Hölt and Holt (see   Holt  ). Compare   Hoelter  ."]},{"name":"Holtman","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Holt   + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","Americanized form of German   Holtmann  ."]},{"name":"Holtmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Udo, Aloys, Hans, Heinz.","North German: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bjorg, Erik, Helmer, Hjalmer, Knute, Nels, Nordahl, Selmer, Swen, Thorvald.","North German: variant of   Holt  .","North German: habitational name from any of several places so named."]},{"name":"Hoult","meanings":["English: variant of   Holt  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":57,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agneta Holt was born in 1280, in Coughton, Warwickshire, England, her father, John Del Holte II, was 25 and her mother, Joan Audley, was 32. She had at least 1 daughter with William de Montfort. She died in 1340, in France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1280–1340":"1280–1340","1275–1347":"1275–1347","1276–1330":"1276–1330","1308–1362":"1308–1362","1255–1317